            <h3>Agree who does what</h3>

            <p>You need to agree who is responsible and accountable for Secure by Design activities. For example, a developer is responsible for [xxx xx xxx xxx]. Your delivery lead is accountable for making sure it happens. </p>

            <p>Check <a href="https://www.security.gov.uk/guidance/secure-by-design/activities/agreeing-roles-and-responsibilities" target="_blank">GOV.UK guidance on roles and responsibilities<span class="govuk-visually-hidden"> (opens in a new tab)</span></a>. The guidance includes a template you can use.</p>

            <h3>Appoint a Senior Responsible Owner</h3>

            <p>If you do not have a Senior Responsible Officer (SRO), someone in your team needs to take on the role. </p>
            
            <p>Your SRO needs to be someone with authority and experience in risk management, for example a product or service owner. If you do not have someone suitable, your project sponsor can be your SRO.</p>
            <p>SROs are usually supported by security and delivery leads. If you do not have anyone on your team with cyber security experience, you need to fill that role.</p>

             <h2 id="agree-your-strategy">Agree your strategy</h2>

            <p>To help you plan your approach to Secure by Design, create a cyber risk management strategy.</p>

            <p>Your strategy should include:</p>

            <ul>
              <li>how much risk is acceptable for your technology or service</li>
              <li>managing cyber security risks throughout the life of the project</li>
              <li>adding cyber security to existing governance</li>
              <li>considerations for stakeholders, including suppliers </li>
              <li>how you will monitor and share cyber security threats</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Set your risk appetite</h3>

            <p>You need to define and publish how much risk is acceptable to your technology or service. For example [add an example here, possibly about personal data].</p>
            <p>Many top level budgets have risk appetite statements. Check the risk appetite statement for your organisation. Your project's risk appetite will need to follow it.</p>
            
